  "response": "No, humans are definitely not reproducing like rabbits. Here's why:\n\n*   **Gestation Period:** Rabbits have a very short gestation period (around 30 days). Humans have a gestation period of approximately 9 months (280 days).\n*   **Litter Size:** Rabbits have multiple offspring in a litter (typically 4-12 baby rabbits per litter). Humans usually have one baby at a time, with twins or multiple births being less common.\n*   **Reproductive Maturity:** Rabbits reach sexual maturity and can start reproducing at a very young age (as early as 3-6 months). Humans typically don't reach sexual maturity until their teenage years.\n*   **Frequency of Reproduction:** Rabbits can have multiple litters per year, sometimes as often as every month. Humans, due to the longer gestation period and the time it takes to recover after childbirth, cannot reproduce as frequently.\n\nThe phrase \"reproducing like rabbits\" is used to describe rapid population growth due to a high rate of reproduction. Human population growth is influenced by many factors, including birth rates, death rates, access to healthcare, economic conditions, and cultural norms. While the human population has grown significantly over the past few centuries, the rate of growth is nowhere near the reproductive capacity of rabbits.",
